    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I think common way of telling a program to stop parsing argument is to use `--`. the\n\"`python -m pip install --upgrade pip` obviously work\" seem a bit non obvious to me. \n\nBypassing IPython parsing just for `-m` might be a bit dangerous, but you can do \n`ipython -m pip` , stop parsing argument with `--` and that give the rest of flags for pip:\n\n```\n$ ipython -m  pip -- install --upgrade pip\nDownloading/unpacking pip from https://pypi.python.org/packages/py2.py3/p/pip/pip-6.0.3-py2.py3-none-any.whl#md5=1ac546485f75a8cf257a8f1a40aa51f5\n  Downloading pip-6.0.3-py2.py3-none-any.whl (1.3MB): 1.3MB downloaded\nInstalling collected packages: pip\n  Found existing installation: pip 1.5.6\n    Uninstalling pip:\n      Successfully uninstalled pip\nSuccessfully installed pip\nCleaning up...\n```\n\nDoes that seem like a good solution ? \n"
  },
